  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
      <p>Emotional intelligence arrived in the popular imagination in 1995, when Daniel Goleman published a book asserting that EQ — emotional quotient — was a better predictor of life success than IQ. The claim was striking, the timing was perfect, and the corporate world adopted it immediately. By the early 2000s, every mid-sized organization had an EI training program. Every HR department had EI assessments. Emotional intelligence became the psychological construct that productivity seminars ran on.</p>

      <p>The science has complicated the story since then in ways that neither the popular enthusiasm nor the training industry has adequately acknowledged. The research consensus is, in short: emotional intelligence is real, the original market claims were exaggerated, and most of what companies assess and train under the EI banner has questionable relationship to the actual construct.</p>

      <p>This is worth understanding not to dismiss the concept — which has genuine scientific standing — but to separate the signal from the substantial noise that now surrounds it.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="what-ei-actually-is" class="reveal">
      <h2>What Emotional Intelligence Actually Is</h2>

      <p>The original scientific model, developed by psychologists Peter Salovey and John Mayer before Goleman popularized their work, defined emotional intelligence as a specific set of cognitive abilities:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Perceiving emotions</strong> accurately — reading emotional signals in faces, voices, and body language</li>
        <li><strong>Using emotions</strong> to facilitate thinking — leveraging emotional states to guide cognitive processes</li>
        <li><strong>Understanding emotions</strong> — knowledge of how emotions evolve, blend, and interact</li>
        <li><strong>Managing emotions</strong> — the capacity to regulate your own emotional states and influence others'</li>
      </ul>

      <p>This is an ability model: emotional intelligence as a set of skills that can be measured with performance tests, like other cognitive abilities. You either perceive the emotion in a face accurately or you don't. You either understand that jealousy and resentment often share a common origin or you don't. The measurement is relatively objective.</p>

      <p>Goleman's popularized version expanded this considerably, including personality traits like empathy, motivation, and social skills in the definition. This expansion made EI more appealing as a corporate concept — it now covered a sweeping range of desirable characteristics — while simultaneously making it nearly impossible to measure rigorously, since personality traits and cognitive abilities are different kinds of things that require different assessment methods.</p>

      <p>Most EI assessments used in corporate settings measure the Goleman-style trait version — essentially, asking people to rate themselves on how empathetic, emotionally aware, and socially skilled they are. The problem is well-documented: self-report assessments of emotional intelligence correlate substantially with personality traits (particularly agreeableness, extraversion, and emotional stability) and with general measures of psychological well-being. They don't clearly measure anything above and beyond what those simpler constructs would predict.</p>

      <p>The Salovey-Mayer ability model, assessed through performance tests, shows more discriminant validity — it predicts outcomes that personality and IQ don't, particularly in social and interpersonal domains.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"Emotional intelligence is real, the original market claims were exaggerated, and most of what companies assess and train under the EI banner has questionable relationship to the actual construct."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="what-evidence-shows" class="reveal">
      <h2>What the Evidence Shows</h2>

      <p>After three decades of research and considerable controversy, a reasonable scientific summary looks like this:</p>

      <p><strong>Emotionally intelligent individuals, as measured by ability tests, show better performance in specifically social contexts.</strong> They are more accurate at reading emotional expressions, better at predicting how others will feel in hypothetical situations, more effective in negotiation and conflict resolution, and rated more effective by others in interpersonal roles. The effect sizes are real but not as sweeping as the popular literature implied.</p>

      <p><strong>The prediction of career success is more modest than Goleman claimed.</strong> A comprehensive meta-analysis across over 130 studies found that ability EI predicts job performance with an effect size roughly equivalent to personality traits — meaningful but not transformative, and considerably smaller than the effects of cognitive ability and conscientiousness. The specific contexts where EI shows the strongest predictive validity are those explicitly involving emotional information: service roles, caregiving, leadership, and interpersonal communication. In technical roles with limited social complexity, the predictive advantage largely disappears.</p>

      <p><strong>Trait EI shows better prediction of wellbeing than ability.</strong> Measuring emotional intelligence as a personality disposition — how people tend to feel about and manage their emotions — predicts life satisfaction, mental health outcomes, and relationship quality with respectable effect sizes. This is not surprising: people who have stable, positive emotional dispositions, who don't catastrophize, and who generally feel competent to manage their emotional lives do better on wellbeing measures.</p>

      <p><strong>EI training has a mixed evidence base.</strong> Interventions designed to improve emotional intelligence show modest effects in some studies and null effects in others. The most promising results are from targeted skills training — specifically training in emotion recognition, perspective-taking, and emotion regulation — rather than from the broad, values-oriented EI programs that corporations typically deploy.</p>
    </section>

